1.1 Developments in East Asia
...

Essential Question

How did developments in China and the rest of East Asia between c.1200 and c.1450 reflect continuity, innovation, and diversity

Dynasties

The relationships between dynasties are usually just one being the dominant one, then just 100 years of chaos, and then another one comes to try to continue the work of the last one, which ended up in a huge back and fourth of opinions that were in control, from emperors wanting to bring back old traditions, and emperors who wanted to purify them.

Dynasties
...

  1. Tang Dynasty
  2. Song Dynasty
Brief information on China

China is currently considered as one huge entity, but that doesn't really make sense culturally, since China has so many different religions and philosophies on its territory. Also, until the 1900s everyone was basically copying China, which is not surprising since they were one of the biggest economies in the world.

Phisolophies & Religion
...

China has ancient religions that are hard to grasp and that all came from different regions in China, but here are some important ones:

  • Confucianism
  • Taoism

1.2 Developments in Dar al-Islam
...

Translated to "The House of Islam"
...

Essential Question

In the period c.1200 to c.1450, how did Islamic states arise, and how did major religious systems shape society?

A really old religion, Zoroastrianism, is ancestral to Iran and was actually what came before Iran.

Baghdad

Baghdad was basically the center of the world at that time, it had a lot of different ideas converging on it because of the Silk Road, and with all the money it had fundamentally the best education at that time.

Death of Mohammad and the Spread of Islam

After the death of Mohammad in c.632, Islam spread extremely fast through merchants and political action. The reason why it spread so fast, is because honestly, Islam had its message aimed at the poor.

Caliphates

Many of the Caliphates had significant intellectual, technological, and artistic advancements during this time period, an example of this being House of Wisdom.

The Bible was written in Greek, Greek was the scholarly language.

Islam > Islam in a Nutshell
...

The Abbasids
...

Invasions and Shifts in Trade Routes

The Abbasid Caliphate (750-1258)
  • The third Caliphate that links itself to Muhammad's uncle (Just like in Christianism people try to link themselves to the lineage of the apostles, Abbas bin Abd al-Muttalib (566-653 CE), from whom the dynasty takes its name.
  • Ruled from Baghdad, known as the Golden Age of Islam, evidence of this is the House of Wisdom.
  • The Abbasids were led by Arabs and Persians, yet the next generation spread further largely shaped by Turks from Central Asia, yet mixed with localities: Next Generations
Egyptian Mamluks (1250-1517)
  • Arabs often purchased slaves. Mamluks were mostly ethnic Turks from Central Asia served as soldiers and could work their way up to be bureaucrats.
  • Remember: even though they had slaves, the slaves could still go up social classes and stop being slaves.

Post-Abbasid Caliphates

...

Essential Question

How did the beliefs and practices of the predominant religions, agricultural practices, and political decentralization affect European society from c. 1200 to c. 1450?

Background
...

The decline of the Roman Empire > 500 CE caused small kingdoms to rise due to the fragmentation.

Little Ice Age

During these times the temperature was colder than normal, worsening crop production.

Trade declined, intellectual life receded, and the Roman Catholic Church unified Europe.
